1. Temporal (Time) FieldsThese fields define when the trade occurred.Field NameData TypeDescription & Example DatarefYearIntegerThe 4-digit year the trade occurred (e.g., 2024).refMonthIntegerThe 1- or 2-digit month the trade occurred (e.g., 5 for May).periodInteger/StringThe concatenated year and month used for batching (e.g., 202405). Note: Always cast this as a String in your Silver layer so you can easily parse it into a DateTime object.

2. Geographic & Directional FieldsThese fields define who is trading and where the goods are going.Field NameData TypeDescription & Example DataflowCode / flowDescStringIndicates the direction of trade. X for Export, M for Import.reporterCode / reporterISOInt / StringThe country reporting the data to the UN. (e.g., 97 / EUR for European Union).reporterDescStringThe human-readable name of the reporting country/bloc (e.g., European Union).partnerCode / partnerISOInt / StringThe primary trading partner (e.g., 156 / CHN). For imports, this is the Country of Origin. For exports, the Country of Destination.partnerDescStringThe human-readable name of the partner country (e.g., China).partner2Code / partner2ISOInt / StringThe secondary partner (Country of Consignment). For your dataset, this will almost always be 0 / W00 (World) because you standardized your extraction to avoid double-counting.

Product (Commodity) FieldsThese fields define what is physically on the ship.Field NameData TypeDescription & Example DatacmdCodeStringThe Harmonized System (HS) code. Crucial: Keep this as a String so codes with leading zeros (like 0901) don't break. (e.g., 1001, 2709).cmdDescStringThe official description of the commodity (e.g., Wheat and meslin, Petroleum oils and oils obtained from bituminous minerals; crude).aggrLevelIntegerThe hierarchy level of the HS code. Because we fixed your API call, this should consistently be 4 across your Gold tables.

Quantitative (Metrics) FieldsThis is the core numerical data you will use to build your Looker Studio charts, calculate unit prices, and detect chokepoint delays.Field NameData TypeDescription & Example DataprimaryValueFloatThe Economic Value (Price): The total monetary value of the trade shipment, standardized in US Dollars (USD). (e.g., $126,639.81).netWgtFloatThe Physical Volume: The net physical weight of the commodity in kilograms (kg). Excludes shipping containers and packaging. (e.g., 198,759.51 kg).qtyFloatThe quantity of the item based on its specific qtyUnitCode. For oil and grain, this usually perfectly mirrors netWgt, but for things like cars, it would be "number of items".qtyUnitAbbrStringThe abbreviation of the unit of measurement used in qty (e.g., kg for kilograms, l for liters).

Metadata & Flags (Optional for BI, Good for Silver Layer)The UN includes flags to tell you if the data is estimated. You generally drop these in the Silver layer, but they are good to document.Field NameData TypeDescription & Example DataisNetWgtEstimatedBooleanReturns True if the reporting country didn't provide a weight, forcing the UN to mathematically estimate it based on the primaryValue.motDescStringMode of Transport (e.g., Sea, Air). Warning: Many countries do not reliably report this, so it often defaults to blank or "TOTAL". Rely on your geographic inference instead.isReportedBooleanReturns True if the data was officially reported by the customs agency, and False if the UN imputed it based on mirror statistics.